@johnstafford220  There isn't really a gaming use case for the 5090 that justifies $2000. And AIBs are all going to cost $2400-3000+ after tax.

The 5090 doesn't beat the 4090 by enough for almost anyone to justify moving on from their 4k@120Hz or 4k@144Hz monitors. To make things worse, the people buying these will almost all want the best monitor tech available...that's OLED. OLED at high refresh rates (especially above 120Hz) currently has a very serious flickering issue on all panels when using VRR. This means that if you're buying a 5090, you're also likely to be getting a 4k to 5k @165Hz to 240Hz OLED and then having to turn off VRR. The cheapest decent monitor in that spec range is about $1000 after taxes, so people will often be spending $3400-4400 just to turn off VRR in many/most scenarios   and move on from an already excellent 4k@120Hz/144Hz OLED with VRR experience.

I spend whatever I want on my computer (9800x3d, 4090, probably nearing $10k for my setup ATM), and this will probably be only the second generation I've ever skipped (other being 2000 series) in almost 10 years. Fourth generation skipped in almost 20 years.   If I'm doubting getting a 5090, who isn't?
